---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ContentImage from '../../components/ContentImage.astro';
import caneVsSouthern from '../../assets/images/canetoad-vs-southern.jpg';
import southernToadNative from '../../assets/images/southern-toad-native.webp';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Cane Toad vs Southern Toad: Key Identification Differences"
  description="Cane toad vs southern toad guide for Florida homeowners. Learn visual differences, pet safety implications, and what to do when identification is uncertain."
>
  <div class="urgency">
    <strong>Unsure after pet contact?</strong> Treat it as urgent and follow the <a href="/cane-toad-dog-poisoning/">emergency response guide</a>.
  </div>

  <div class="hero">
    <h1>Cane Toad vs Southern Toad</h1>
    <p>Correct identification is critical in Florida. Cane toads are invasive and dangerous to pets, while southern toads are native and should not be harmed.</p>
    <a href="/cane-toad-removal/" class="btn btn-lg">Get Help With Toad Removal -></a>
  </div>

  <div class="content">
    <figure class="content-figure">
      <ContentImage
        src={caneVsSouthern}
        alt="Side-by-side comparison of invasive cane toad and native southern toad showing size and head shape differences"
      />
      <figcaption>Cane toads are larger, with prominent parotoid glands; southern toads are smaller with cranial ridges on the head — do not harm native species.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>Cane Toad Identification Features</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Larger body size, often much bigger than native toads</li>
      <li>Large toxin glands behind the shoulders</li>
      <li>Heavy, stocky appearance with smooth head profile</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Southern Toad Identification Features</h2>
    <figure class="content-figure">
      <ContentImage
        src={southernToadNative}
        alt="Native southern toad in natural Florida habitat — smaller build and visible cranial ridges compared with cane toads"
      />
      <figcaption>Native southern toads are part of healthy local ecosystems and should be left alone.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <ul>
      <li>Smaller average size</li>
      <li>Visible cranial ridges and knobs on the head</li>
      <li>Less pronounced toxin gland shape</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why This Difference Matters for SEO and Safety</h2>
    <p>Many homeowners search both "cane toad vs southern toad" and "bufo toad identification." Accurate identification reduces pet risk and prevents harm to native species.</p>

    <h2>What To Do If You Are Not Sure</h2>
    <p>Use caution around pets, document the toad safely, and contact a professional if activity is recurring. When in doubt, prioritize emergency action for any suspected toxin exposure.</p>

    <h2>FAQ</h2>
    <div class="faq">
      <details><summary>Are cane toads and bufo toads the same?</summary><p>Yes. Bufo toad is a common name for the invasive cane toad.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Is the southern toad dangerous like a cane toad?</summary><p>Southern toads are native and generally lower risk than cane toads, but any pet symptoms should be treated seriously.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Can I remove cane toads legally in Florida?</summary><p>Yes, humane removal of invasive cane toads is allowed.</p></details>
    </div>

    <p>Already seeing toads? <a href="/cane-toad-removal/">Connect with a removal pro -></a></p>
    <p>More context: <a href="/cane-toad-florida/">Cane Toad Florida guide -></a></p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
